      <section eId="sec_CCRP-930-3">
        <num>CCRP 930.3</num>
        <heading>930.3.  Grounds</heading>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_1">
          <num>(1)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The conviction was obtained in violation of the constitution of the United States
or the state of Louisiana.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_2">
          <num>(2)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The court exceeded its jurisdiction.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_3">
          <num>(3)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The conviction or sentence subjected him to double jeopardy.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_4">
          <num>(4)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The limitations on the institution of prosecution had expired.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_5">
          <num>(5)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The statute creating the offense for which he was convicted and sentenced is
unconstitutional.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_6">
          <num>(6)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The conviction or sentence constitute the ex post facto application of law in
violation of the constitution of the United States or the state of Louisiana.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_7">
          <num>(7)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The results of DNA testing performed pursuant to an application granted under
Article 926.1 proves by clear and convincing evidence that the petitioner is factually innocent
of the crime for which he was convicted.</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <subsection eId="CCRP-930-3__subsec_8">
          <num>(8)</num>
          <content>
            <p>The petitioner is determined by clear and convincing evidence to be factually
innocent under Article 926.2.
Added by</p>
          </content>
        </subsection>
        <authorialNote marker="source">
          <p>Source: https://www.legis.la.gov/legis/Law.aspx?d=112944</p>
        </authorialNote>
      </section>
